x4freetext: Experiment performed at FN Tandem Van
de Graaff accelerator at the Florida State
University, John D. Fox Superconducting Linear
Accelerator facility.
Pure helium gas with purity 99.9% was used as the
target. The pressure of the helium gas in the chamber
was adjusted for the beam to stop completely inside
the chamber before reaching the detectors
Array of silicon detectors was placed inside the
chamber at angles ranging from 0deg to 60deg in steps
of 5deg to detect the recoiling alpha particles.
The thick target inverse kinematics (TTIK)
technique was used
Alpha particle energy was calculated from particle
kinematics. The spectra of alpha particles measured in
the laboratory frame were converted into c.m.
excitation functions. Because of the extended gas
target, the scattering angle is not fixed and has to
be calculated from the energy of the recoil alpha
particle and the known location of the detectors.
The energy loss of an alpha particle and the solid
angle also depend on the location of the interaction
point and have to be calculated for each energy bin in
the measured spectrum. This was done using a code which
takes into account the relevant experimental conditions
Statistical uncertainty
Compiled by S.H.
